Set Memory Map
Special

This instruction sets the C65 or MEGA65 style memory map, depending
on the values in the Accumulator, X, Y and Z registers.

It is a best practice to not perform a MAP instruction in a memory region whose map is changing. The CPU changes memory settings immediately when performing the MAP instruction. The program counter will use the new memory map to locate the next instruction.

\underline{NOTE}: The MAP instruction disables interrupts, overriding the I flag, until the next EOM instruction. EOM (byte EA) is also used as a compound instruction prefix for 32-bit indirect addressing. Such an instruction will behave as an EOM instruction after a MAP instruction.

Further information on this instruction is available in Appendix \ref{cha:cpu}.

\subsubsection*{Side effects}
\begin{itemize}
\item The memory map is immediately changed to that requested.
\item All interrupts, including Non-Maskable Interrupts (NMIs) are
blocked from occurring until an EOM (NOP) instruction is encountered.
\end{itemize}